## Go further

### A. See scope behavior clearly

```python
name = "outside"

def demo():
    name = "inside"
    print(name)

demo()
print(name)
```

### B. Use `nonlocal`

```python
def counter():
    count = 0

    def increase():
        nonlocal count
        count += 1
        print(count)

    increase()
    increase()

counter()
```

### C. Watch out for accidental locals

```python
score = 10

def update():
    score = score + 1
```

That causes an error, because Python treats `score` as local when it sees the assignment. The FAQ explains this local/global rule. ([Python documentation][3])

